76561198044338757,Recommended,227000,18398375,"Posted: 9 October, 2015",all,Load of Barnacles,"As a person who doesn't enjoy point and click games whatsoever, I have already played through the entire story three times now. This game has one of the most compelling storylines I have seen in a long time and, despite its mechanical simplicity, has easily become one of my favorite titles. The artwork is absolutely gorgeous and the voice acting is incredible. The perfect balance of humor and darkness creates an atmosphere that is not easy to replicate in a game. If you're looking for a game with an excellent story and moderately difficult puzzles to complete along the way, this game is perfect."
,Recommended,227000,18574771,"Posted: 19 October, 2015",all,Baphomet,"In Primordia, you play the role of a robotic nomad named Horatio struggling to find his way through a post-apocalyptic wasteland. Through your searches, you managed to find a power source capable of helping you re-build a derelict spacecraft. All seems well until an unknown assailant ambushes you and steals the power source, forcing you to chase after it or face a slow death in the desert wastes. Thankfully you have your witty and sarcastic sidekick, Crispin, to help you make your way through the various obstacles you will inevitably face.Being a point-and-click adventure game, most of the gameplay will revolve around you combining items with other items or using them on various places to solve puzzles and progress the plot. You also get a special button for using Crispin on things, either to help you out or just to hear more of his banter. At any point in the game you can also click on him for idle chatter where he will reveal clues about what you should do next. The game also offers a data pouch to help save critical information (so you don’t need to write much down) as well as a map for fast travel.Most of the puzzles in Primordia are pretty straightforward and Horatio will give you obvious clues whenever you get close to solving one. The only part I found to be particularly tricky was a text-parser based puzzle that required you to stumble through various typos, secret phrases, and acronyms using your keyboard to input queries. But even that was pretty simple once you figured out the trick behind it.One thing I really liked about this game was the overall cozy atmosphere observed through the calming visuals and music. It kind of reminds me of old 70s/80s era sci-fi animated movies in scenes where the character would be walking through some trippy landscape to a synth-heavy soundtrack. Most of the voices are pretty well done too (for such a small studio).As a whole, Primordia is entertaining without being overly hard on the player and is worth looking into for anyone who is a fan of classic adventure games and sci-fi."
