,Recommended,227000,35216845,Posted: 25 September,all,Pirateguybrush,"As someone who plays a lot of adventure games, I can't recommend Primordia highly enough.  The story and worldbuilding are outstanding, the actors deliver universally solid performances, and the atmosphere is wonderfully crafted.  The characters are interesting, layered and well written, and really work to draw you into the world.What really stands out though, are the puzzles.  In many newer adventure games, these act largely as roadblocks to progress, and fall back on tried and true formulas we've all solved many times before.  Primordia has some great new puzzle ideas that I don't recall seeing in other adventure games, as well as puzzles with multiple solutions.  They're well integrated with the story, and are challenging without being illogical or ridiculous.Highly recommended."
,Recommended,227000,13171746,"Posted: 30 November, 2014",all,Silva,"The first thing you will probably notice about Primordia is that it is a beautiful game. The graphics are pixellated, but not in the sense often used by amateur indie designers as an obvious cost-cutting measure. This is pixel art at its finest: lovingly crafted details in every background and most characters show that the game's artist took their work extremely seriously. That effort paid off in spades.The second thing you will probably notice about Primordia is that almost everything about it is bleak. This is not the post-apocalyptic world of Fallout, where things have gone to hell but black comedy keeps things from getting too dark. There is humor in the game, but it works in spite of the world being broken, not because of it. Humanity is extinct, its robotic creations and their creations in turn forming what qualifies for society in Primordia's shattered world. Energy is life, and power is running out.The third thing you will notice is that often the game works in a far more logical way than others in its genre might lead you to expect. Early on you see a lantern on a high shelf your character cannot reach. The solution? Ask your hovering robot sidekick to push it down. There are a lot of moments like that in Primordia, where logic prevails over the typical adventure game ""must be as drunk as the original designer to comprehend"" school of puzzles.That said, there are still moments where you may not figure out on your own. I had to look things up at least a couple times in my playthrough to advance. Not everyone will, and I would discourage players from reading up except as a last resort. The puzzles make up a huge chunk of the game. If they are not your thing, I would say the game is still worth playing with a guide for the atmosphere alone."
