76561198027355802,Recommended,227000,10161695,"Posted: 18 May, 2014",all,fairyhedgehog,"Excellent old-school point and click adventure. Great storyline and characters, easy to use interface. Left click to use, right click to look at, and several options to speed things up, such as the map and the data pouch which records all important clues.I needed help to reach the ending, and then help to get a good ending, but all the puzzles were logical and none felt random or unfair. You do sometimes need to go back to somewhere you've already visited and speak to someone again but much less so than in many games.I found this walkthough useful:http://www.gamezebo.com/games/primordia/walkthrough-cheats-strategy-guide#chapter-2-finding-arbiterbut it does contain spoilers, so I only used it when totally stuck.The resolution is low and I found the visuals rather darker (ie harder to see) than I'd have liked but those were minor quibbles and I enjoyed the game hugely."
,Recommended,227000,10434250,"Posted: 11 June, 2014",all,Typhoone,"I've been playing a lot of indie point-and-clicks lately; Primordia stands out because of its writing and setting. It has a LucasArts Loom vibe to it, with the protagonist Horation NullBuilt conjuring up an idea of what Bobin Threadbare would be if he was competent and decided to use his amnesia to his advantage. Yes, both characters have amnesia, have lost their home communities, and the fabric of society quite literally rests on their creations. Elements of the story definitely seem similar. The setting of Primordia is more exciting. It's a colorful combination of dystopia, cyberpunk, and steampunk. While that mix is becoming more and more common these days, finding 'good' games in that genre is still rare.I mentioned the writing: the story is captivating if only to explore the lore, and the main plot-arc is mediocre. The dialog writing is where the game shines; Horatio's sidekick levitating robot Crispin is a very well written NPC that integrates into the game nicely. The character is used to solve some puzzles, though not too much, and offers rather direct walkthrough-type tips if the protagonist is stuck.With it's marvelous writing, I wanted Primordia to feature more NPCs and dialog quests. A particular stand-out quest involves a logic puzzle attempting to legally assign the surname of a pet robot. While the logic is difficult to follow without pen and paper handy, the writing and voice-acting attempts to seduce the player away from choosing the logical option and I was tempted to go down a logically-flawed path (which the game teased would result in different endings and impact late-game quests). Rarely does game-dialog inspire this anymore, and it is where indie games such as Primordia stand a cut above the rest.The game has a relatively short playthrough and the puzzles become more difficult, sometimes to the level of ridiculousness, later in the game. This is caused by the game too early allowing me to use multiple items for different quests, and in the late game suffering through trying every permutation of item combination to solve the puzzles. Nonetheless, I would recommend this game to a casual or hardcore adventure gamer, as it is both enjoyable and tells a well-written, albeit cliche story."
