es find out eventually that the megacycles are brain power, we could also call it processing power. Anyways, the story goes along and Horatio finds out that his power core is stored on the big tower where Metromind is. He then goes on to try and get it back and that's when things take a darker turn. BUUUUUT I don't want to spoil the ending for anyone who might have read the spoil alert and then thinks to theirselfs ""you know what, Imma read it anyways"".The story is great, the caracthers are great, the puzzles are excellent and there are multiple endings which means you can replay the game and let me tell you, you will want to replay the game because it is so damn good!I would rate it an honest 9.5/10 , I would even dare to give it a 10/10 .Amazing game and for 10 euros, it is a bargain of a lifetime"
,Recommended,227000,15415226,"Posted: 17 April, 2015",all,RuySan,"Wow, another great entry into this new golden age of adventure games. Primordia does so many things right, stuff that should be common in every game of this genre, like multiple solutions to puzzles, branching paths and multiple endings.Both the story and atmosphere are great, and Crispin, the sidekick, serves not only as a great jokester, but also as a nice hint system that ensures that we are not left wandering aimlessly, like in many old adventure games.The game is quite short, but it’s better for it, as it doesn’t suffer from overreach, and it achieves the goal of telling a good story and exploring interesting themes.There’s not many downsides to this game, but one particular puzzle, near the end of the game (involving a kiosk), annoyed me, and didn’t played by the same rules as the rest of the game. I also thought that the voice of Horatio never felt appropriate for a robot (it’s the same actor as the main character of Gemini Rue, but in that case it fit great) , but it’s just a minor quibble. The rest of the cast and characters are great."
