,Recommended,227000,20778475,"Posted: 26 January, 2016",all,TN Hoff,"A mysterious past is slowly unveiled in a post-apocalyptic art-noveau cyberpunk world.If you like robots, themes of AI, and/or adventure games - especially classic ones - this game is for you.The game follows the pretty standard adventure mechanic - click on things to make things happen - sometimes click on things with things from your inventory, or mix things in your inventory together until they become clickable on other things.  Take notes.  (Most of which actually happens for you with the in-game ""data-pad"".)  Solve puzzles with said notes.The game runs at 640x400 resolution - which can be off-putting to some, but really lends to the retro-adventure feel of the game, and I've come to love it.  (On my 1080p tv, it won't actually fill up the whole screen, but it doesn't really bother me.)  That said - I highly recommend going into the options menu and chosing the ""DX"" display mode as opposed to D3D if it works for you - the sprites mesh with the backgrounds much better this way in my opinion.  DOS nostalgia!What really shines in Primordia is the story - and the art.  They come together to create a fascinating atmosphere that makes me want to revisit the game again and again - and the developer commentary is great on a second or third playthrough.  The excellent voice acting and seven or so potential endings don't hurt, either.  (The narrator from Bastion plays the main character - and the sidekick that follows you through the game is entertaining at every turn.)  The music and sound mesh well with the art to create an engrossing atmosphere - despite the retro low-res graphics.There aren't many puzzles in the ""puzzle game"" sense - but there is plenty of puzzling to be done in the game in terms of figuring out how things fit together, what things mean, and what the significance of certain items or pieces of information may be.  The story is mostly linear, but there are a few opportunities to take different approaches to solve situations - especially near the end.  Observation and careful contemplation are rewarded.The setting is in the distant future in a post-human world - no organic life is to be found anywhere - even the bugs and little things swimming in the sewers are machines - but make no mistake, they have lives and thoughts of their own, and are no less interesting than any human character.  And for the robot fan, there are references to other robots from both popular and obscure culture everywhere - along with a videogame reference or two.  MST3K, Short Circuit, Metropolis, and Fallout - just to name a few.I would highly recommend this game to any fan of classic graphic adventures, narrative-driven games, or robots."
76561197992615560,Recommended,227000,25262646,"Posted: 30 August, 2016",all,Stormbrooke,"If story is more important for you in a game than mechanics or visuals than you will enjoy Primordia as it is a decently written story.> Great game lore / interesting setting> Great plot and semi twist if you don't see it coming, I enjoyed the little seeds throughout the game like the ship being named ""UNIIC""(VGER anyone?).If the writer reads this not that I minded the ending but I think the twist would have had even more punch if Horus had followed through with his mission instead of Metromind carrying it out, big bad being the big bad is not as fun of a twist as the good guy was the bad guy. Would have made the final choice more interesting and a more interesting realization for the player ""I'm a humanist trying to save humanity but I killed them?"", my two cents as a wannabe writer, was still good though> Main character deals with interesting themes, and can choose different paths, ""Progress needs transformation needs art needs freedom"" reminded me of 'what can change the nature of a man' from Planescape: Torment... was interesting to think about it, as were the logical arguments of the robots> Sidekick character is more funny and likeable than most comedic relief companion characters, reminded me a lot of Morte from Planescape:Torment while still being unique and memorable as his own characterI felt a great deal of loss after he died, almost found myself getting angry like the main character and strongly felt his absense in the scenes following his death, great immersion!Mild Cons:> Puzzles were okay, not overly hard or easy. I enjoyed the logic puzzles more so than go search a map for random item (I could see others minding those quests less), the wingman quest though had me chuckle> Game is short, 9 hrs for me with frequent pauses leaving the game running while I took breaks> Graphics are reto pixels but not bad if you zoom out, took my eyes a bit to adjust in the beginningFor me money well spent, memorable story."
