76561197966557804,Recommended,227000,30066508,Posted: 20 February,all,The Rabid Otter,"Primordia centers on the travails of two robots, Horatio and Crispen, who live in what is eventually revealed to be a warship on the edge of the ruins of a great city, Metropol. Their wasteland idyll is broken when another robot appears and steals the pair's power core. As robots, they require power, and embark upon a journey in a wasteland that reflects the splendour of a now dead world.Historically, I am not a fan of point-and-click adventure games.  But this game may have changed that. While I did occassionally cheat and look for solutions online, the tale of our two robots drew me in like the scent of a pitcher plant draws in flies. Upon reflection, the story reminds me of something that would have been published in Metal Hurlant three or more decades ago (minus the gratutious sex).The game makes explicit, though with subtle insertion, reference to other  speculative fiction masterpieces from multiple media. Fallout, Half-Life and A Canticle for Liebowitz being the ones I could clearly identify. Furthermore, the development team, usually the writer, provide liner notes revealing the design decisions they made in making this compelling tale. As someone interested in the division of labor in video game production, this was fascinating in its own right.If you like dystopian or melancholoy worldbuilding, this game is for you."
